            <h2>Letter B</h2>
            <p>Let's explore the sign for the letter 'B'. In ASL, the 'B' sign is quite distinct and can be viewed as
                the opposite of the 'A' sign. It's a simple yet essential sign in the ASL alphabet and is used in
                various ASL words. Understanding and mastering the 'B' sign is crucial for effective communication in
                ASL. Now, let's learn how to correctly form the sign for 'B'.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Palm Orientation:</strong> Start by facing your palm towards the person you are
                    communicating with. This orientation is important for the visibility of the sign.</li>
                <li><strong>Positioning Fingers 2-5:</strong> Extend fingers 2, 3, 4, and 5 (your index, middle, ring,
                    and pinky fingers) upwards. These fingers should be straight, close together, and pointing up, like
                    soldiers standing in a line.</li>
                <li><strong>Placement of Finger 1 (Thumb):</strong> Now, for your thumb (finger 1), bend it into your
                    palm. It should be comfortably resting against your palm, under your other fingers. This is
                    different from the 'A' sign, where the thumb sticks out.</li>
                <li><strong>Check Your Handshape:</strong> Your hand should now look like a flat, upright surface with
                    all fingers except the thumb pointing upwards. The thumb tucked in gives the distinct 'B' shape.
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>And there you have it, the sign for the letter 'B' in ASL! Practice this sign to get familiar with its
                shape and feel. Remember, the key to the 'B' sign is keeping your four fingers straight and together
                while your thumb rests inside the palm. Enjoy your ASL learning journey!</p>
