                <h2>Letter C</h2>
                <p>The sign for 'C' is quite intuitive and visually representative of the letter itself. Unlike the
                    signs for 'A' and 'B', the 'C' sign involves a different hand orientation and shape, making it
                    unique in the ASL alphabet. Learning to sign the letter 'C' accurately is not only fun but also
                    enhances your understanding of the visual nature of ASL. Let's explore the steps to form the 'C'
                    sign correctly.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Palm Orientation:</strong> Begin with your palm facing sideways, neither towards you nor
                        the person you are communicating with. This side orientation is crucial for forming the 'C'
                        shape accurately.</li>
                    <li><strong>Positioning Your Thumb (Finger 1):</strong> Place your thumb (finger 1) underneath your
                        fingers. It should be slightly bent to start forming the bottom curve of the 'C'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curving Fingers 2-5:</strong> Now, gently curve your index, middle, ring, and pinky
                        fingers (fingers 2, 3, 4, and 5) over your thumb. These fingers should be close together,
                        forming the top part of the 'C' shape. Make sure the curve is clear and distinct.</li>
                    <li><strong>Forming the 'C' Shape:</strong> Adjust your fingers and thumb to create a rounded,
                        'C'-like shape with your hand. The goal is to mimic the shape of the letter 'C' as closely as
                        possible with your hand.</li>
                    <li><strong>Final Check:</strong> Look at your hand to ensure it resembles a 'C'. The open, curved
                        shape of your hand is the key feature of this sign.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>And that's how you sign the letter 'C' in ASL! It's a visually straightforward sign, resembling the
                    letter it represents. Practice forming this sign to become comfortable with it. Remember, the
                    essence of the 'C' sign lies in the curved shape of your hand, capturing the essence of the letter
                    'C'. Happy signing!</p>
